{
  "doc_id": "5496",
  "text": "The dopamine system has also been implicated in the pathophysiology of OCD, as well as other neuropsychiatric phenotypes such as schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] The catechol-O-methyltransferase gene (COMT) is therefore an attractive OCD-candidate gene since it encodes a catabolic dopamine enzyme. The gene has been extensively studied in psychiatric genetics [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , with the majority of association studies genotyping a functional polymorphism that causes a 3-4 fold reduction in enzymatic activity (i.e. Val158Met). [CITATION_7] Studies of the South African Caucasian OCD population have identified this polymorphism as a risk factor for both the disorder [CITATION_8] and certain symptom dimensions within OCD. [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] The low activity 158Met allele was found to be correlated with more severe symptomatology associated with hoarding in male Afrikaner OCD patients [CITATION_11] and in a subsequent study, a cluster of symptoms in South African Caucasian OCD patients that included \"symmetry and ordering\". [CITATION_12] The sexual dimorphism detected with COMT 158Met and the hoarding symptom dimension of OCD by Lochner et al. [CITATION_13] has also been observed with regards to this polymorphism and susceptibility to the disorder. A metaanalysis of COMT-OCD genetic association studies showed that the 158Met allele is associated with OCD in men (P<0.001) [CITATION_14] , making this polymorphism one of the most convincing genetic risk factors for OCD identified to date.",
